<div class="penelope">
  <img src="/img/welcomingcat.png" alt="Penelope the Neocities cat">
  <div class="penelope-Bubble">
    <p>Ready for a secret? Part of your page is <em>invisible</em>. Look at the top of your code &mdash; what's that <code>head</code> thing?</p>
  </div>
</div>

<p>Every web page has two zones:</p>

<ul class="lesson-List">
  <li><strong><code><%= '<body>' %></code></strong> &mdash; everything visitors see. Your heading and paragraphs live here.</li>
  <li><strong><code><%= '<head>' %></code></strong> &mdash; information <em>about</em> the page. Nothing in here appears on the page itself.</li>
</ul>

<p>So what's the head good for? Look inside yours and you'll find this line:</p>

<pre><code class="html"><%= '<title>My First Website</title>' %></code></pre>

<p>The <code><%= '<title>' %></code> is the name of your page. It shows up in the browser tab, in bookmarks, and in search results &mdash; just not on the page itself. Check the little tab at the top of your preview window: it says <em>My First Website</em> right now.</p>

<div class="your-Turn">
  <h4><i class="fa fa-pencil" aria-hidden="true"></i> Your turn</h4>
  <ol>
    <li>Find the <code><%= '<title>' %></code> line inside your <code><%= '<head>' %></code>.</li>
    <li>Change <em>My First Website</em> to a title of your own &mdash; your site's name is a great choice.</li>
    <li>Watch the tab above the preview change, then click <strong>Check My Work</strong>.</li>
  </ol>
</div>

<div class="bonus-Box">
  <h4>New element, same skill</h4>
  <p>Notice you already knew how to do this &mdash; the <code><%= '<title>' %></code> element works just like <code><%= '<p>' %></code> and <code><%= '<h1>' %></code>: opening tag, content, closing tag. Most of HTML is this one pattern over and over.</p>
</div>

<script>
  function lessonCheck(doc, html) {
    if(missingClosingTag(html, 'title'))
      return {ok: false, message: 'Your ' + codeSample('<title>') + ' is missing its closing ' + codeSample('</title>') + ' tag &mdash; without it, the browser thinks your whole page is the title!'}

    var titleTag = doc.querySelector('title')

    if(!titleTag)
      return {ok: false, message: 'Your page lost its ' + codeSample('<title>') + ' element! Add ' + codeSample('<title>Your Title Here</title>') + ' inside the ' + codeSample('<head>') + '.'}

    var titleText = titleTag.textContent.trim()

    if(titleText == '')
      return {ok: false, message: 'Your title is empty. Put your page&rsquo;s name between ' + codeSample('<title>') + ' and ' + codeSample('</title>') + '.'}

    if(titleText == 'My First Website')
      return {ok: false, message: 'That&rsquo;s still the title I gave you! Change it to something that&rsquo;s yours.'}

    return {ok: true, message: 'Look at the tab above your preview &mdash; that&rsquo;s your title up there!'}
  }
</script>
